2 examinations under § 5-2-301 et seq.
3 (B) An individual employed as a technician may shall not:
4 administer or score projective tests
5 (i) Select tests;
6 (ii) Conduct intake assessments;
7 (iii) Conduct clinical interviews including without
8 limitation patient interviews and collateral interviews of relatives, friends
9 of the patient, or other professionals associated with the patient;
10 (iv) Interpret patient data;
11 (v) Communicate test results or treatment
12 recommendations to patients; or
13 (vi) Administer tests in educational institutions.
14 (b)(1) A technician shall have a bachelor's degree from a regionally
15 an accredited institution, preferably with a major in psychology approved by
16 the Arkansas Psychology Board.
17 (2) The basic educational background of a technician shall
18 include passing grades from instruction in:
19 (A) Abnormal psychology;
20 (B) Personality;
21 (C) Psychological statistics; and
22 (D) Psychological testing.
23 (3) As used in this subsection, “passing grade” means:
24 (A) “C” in a letter grading system;
25 (B) “Pass” in a pass/fail system; or
26 (C) “Satisfactory” in a satisfactory/unsatisfactory
27 grading system.
28 (4) A technician who has completed a degree with a nonpsychology
29 major shall have completed course work with passing grades in the subject
30 matter areas listed in subdivision (b)(2) of this section.
31 (5)(A)(2)(A) A technician who does not have this academic
32 background and the academic background under subdivision (b)(1) of this
33 section and who is currently employed by a psychologist shall be provided
34 with specific information to supplement his or her training in
35 neuropsychological psychological test administration.
